nks":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41626"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn infant is born to a mother who did not receive any prenatal care. On examination vital parameters are within normal range. Physical examination of the infant reveals microphthalmia, cleft lip, and cleft palate. There is a punched-out lesion on the patient\u0027s scalp. A loop of bowel covered with a thin membrane is seen protruding from the patient\u0027s abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely associated with this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bicuspid aortic valve","Truncus arteriosus","Horseshoe kidney","Atrialisation of right ventricle","Ventricular septal defect"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has been diagnosed with Patau syndrome (trisomy 13). It is characterised by cutis aplasia (ie, punched out lesion on the scalp), microcephaly, cleft lip/palate, polydactyly, and congenital heart diseases. Patients may also have an omphalocele (ie, a loop of intestines covered by a membranous sac protruding from the midline of the abdomen). The most common congenital heart diseases associated with Patau syndrome are \u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E and patent ductus arteriosus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBicuspid aortic valve \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E horseshoe kidneys\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with Turner syndrome. Turner syndrome present in girls, not boys. It is characterized by the loss of one X chromosome (ie, 45, XO). Turner syndrome is characterized by a webbed neck, short height, widely-spaced nipples, and streak ovaries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETruncus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly associated with DiGeorge syndrome which is an autosomal dominant disorder characterised by impaired development of the 3rd and 4th pharyngeal pouches. This leads to thymic aplasia and hypoparathyroidism. Phenotypically, these patients present with micrognathia, low-set ears, and widely-spaced eyes (ie, hypertelorism). Cutis aplasia and omphalocele are unlikely to be seen in patients with DiGeorge syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with Ebstein anomaly have a malformation of the tricuspid valves leading to the displacement of the valves into the right ventricle. This causes the right ventricle to become functionally a part of the right atrium (commonly referred to as \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0022atrialisation of the right ventricle\u0022\u003C/strong\u003E). Ebstein anomaly is associated with lithium exposure in-utero. It is unlikely to present with clinical features of aplasia cutis, omphalocele, and cleft lip/palate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patau syndrome (trisomy 13) may present with cutis aplasia (ie, punched out lesion on the scalp), microcephaly, cleft lip/palate, polydactyly, and congenital heart diseases such as ventricular septal defects."],"references":["Williams GM, Brady R. Patau Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Internet]. 2021. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538347/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26544"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2476"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1331"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1331"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/226d612e-16a7-422e-9cc5-50a4199d6f1f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/226d612e-16a7-422e-9cc5-50a4199d6f1f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":460,"height":313}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26544"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-20T12:35:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-20T12:35:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"ite